            {
                "heading": "The Mouth of the Prophet — God's Anger and Aaron (4:10-17)",
                "body": "Moses protests that he is 'not a man of words' (lo ish devarim), claiming to be 'heavy of mouth and heavy of tongue' (kaved peh ukhvad lashon). Whether this indicates a speech impediment, lack of rhetorical training, or simply reluctance is debated. God's response is a creation theology of speech: 'Who has made man's mouth? Who makes him mute, or deaf, or seeing, or blind? Is it not I, YHWH?' The creator of the mouth can surely empower its speech. God promises: 'I will be with your mouth' (ehyeh im-pikha) — the ehyeh of the divine name now applied to prophetic empowerment. When Moses finally pleads, 'Please send someone else' (shelach na beyad-tishlach), God's anger burns (yichar af YHWH). This is the only place in the call narrative where divine patience ends. Aaron the Levite is appointed as Moses' navi (spokesman/prophet): Moses will speak God's words to Aaron, and Aaron will speak to the people. The relationship mirrors the prophet-God relationship: 'He shall speak for you to the people, and he shall be your mouth, and you shall be as God to him.' Moses is placed in the position of Elohim to Aaron — a human analogy of the divine council communication structure."
            },
